Introduction

¶

This dataset contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb)

About TMDb:¶

TMDb in a nutshell is a TV and movie database with a social network flavor.

The Movie Database (TMDb) is a community built movie and TV database. Every piece of data has been added by our amazing community dating back to 2008. TMDb's strong international focus and breadth of data is largely unmatched and something we're incredibly proud of. Put simply, we live and breathe community and that's precisely what makes us different. TMDb website

Columns Description:¶

  1. id : identification number for the movie in TMDb.
  2. imdb_id : identification number for the movie in IMDB.

  3. popularity : this one is complicated. according to TMDb description , it could mean many things. for example in case of movies it could be:

    • Number of votes for the day
    • Number of views for the day
    • Number of users who marked it as a "favourite" for the day
    • Number of users who added it to their "watchlist" for the day
    • Release date
    • Number of total votes
    • Previous days score

      unfortunately, in this dataset we don't have a specific information about what popularity actually represent.

  4. budget : the movie's designated budget.

  5. revenue : amount of movie returns.
  6. original_title : the title of the movie.
  7. cast : names of actors and actresses in the movie.
  8. homepage : homepage address for the movie website.
  9. director : name of the director of the movie.
  10. tagline : a popular phrase associated with the movie.
  11. keywords : thematic words describing the movie.
  12. overview : a short description of what a movie is about.
  13. runtime : movie runtime in minutes.
  14. genres : the movie genre or genres to which a movie belongs.
  15. production_companies : name of production companies for a movie.
  16. release_date : exact release date of the movie.
  17. vote_count : number of votes by users for a movie.
  18. vote_average : the average score of the users' vote for a movie.
  19. release_year : year of release of the movie.
  20. budget_adj : budget of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.
  21. revenue_adj : revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Questions to explore:¶

There is a lot of information that this dataset can provide us. Here we will explore and search for answers to some chosen questions which are listed below:

  1. How did several genres fare through the years?
  2. Does a high budget guarantee a high revenue? and which movie has the highest budget to revenue ratio?
  3. Does a movie runtime affect the revenue? and is the average movie runtime increasing over the years?
  4. Who is the most accomplished director in terms of total revenues and total average scores of his movies?
  5. Who are the most productive directors in terms of number of movies made?

before any further steps let's make it easier for us to focus and get rid of columns that will not aid in answering the questions reviewed above. for example, columns like id and imdb_id will not add any thing to our investigation by creating a new modified dataframe that we can handle freely and keeping our original dataframe intact just in case.

To do this we will use numpy's r_ function to concatenate the indices of our desired columns, then use pandas .iloc for column selection based on that.

1. How did several genres fare through the years?¶

In this question we will invesigate the popularity of movie genres by finding the amount of movies in each genres through the year. are they increasing? and with them the popularity of the genre, or are they decreasing? and with them the popularity of the genre.

We will select some genres to track their number of movies through years, our chosen genres are: Action, Comedy, Animation, Horror, Documentary, and Western.

From our look at the dataframe, genres column does not look really inviting.

In [21]:

each cell in the column contain several genres! which will be a problem in our investigation. Thankfully by searching, I found this post on stack overflow, which introduced me to the concept of a dummy variable.

from my understanding, a dummy varible is a generated column with a boolean or 0/1 values that indicate the presence or absence of the data which the column represent. this will help not only in separating each unique string in its own column but also will return a numerical one that we can easily manipulate and use in our calculations.

To create this dummy variable we will use pandas .str.get_dummies() which I found out how to use from its documentation . an important part is the separator between strings in each cell, which is a bar "|" in our column and which is also the default separator in .str.get_dummies(), so we don't have to provide any arguments.

In [10]:
# creating a dummy dataframe from the genres column
genres = df_mod.genres.str.get_dummies()
genres.head(2)

2. Does a high budget guarantee a high revenue? and which movie has the highest budget to revenue ratio?¶

To answer this question we will create a new budgets dataframe containing the budget and revenue columns along with the following:

  • create a new column named budget_level in which we will divide budget into high, middle, and low
  • create a new column named rev_bud_ratio to explore the relationship between both budget and revenue in a quantified manner. this will involve dividing revenue_adj by budget_adj which means we can't have zeros in any of them so that we can get a meaningful result.

Let's start by creating budgets dataframe and dealing with zeros in our columns. also scientific notation is not really necessary in this context, so I will convert both budget_adj and revenue_adj to integers to make it a little bit easier to handle.

Note: we will include also runtime and release_year in the dataframe because we are going to need them in our following question

To remove the zero cells in budget_adj and revenue_adj we will use pandas .query() to get all the rows that does not have zero value in both of these columns. and assigning the result to our budgets dataframe.

In [26]:
# creating budgets dataframe
budgets = df_mod.query('budget_adj != 0 & revenue_adj != 0 ')[['original_title','release_year','budget_adj','revenue_adj','runtime']]

Creating the budget_level column¶

To create this colum we will do the following:

  • movies below median budget will be labelled low.
  • movies budgets between the median and the 3rd quartile will be labelled medium
  • movies with budgets above the 3rd quartile will be labelled high.

according to the above criteria we create the bin edges and names with which pandas cut will work.

So, let's get our budget_adj summary statistics now and get going.

In [28]:
# summary stats for budget_adj
budgets['budget_adj'].describe()

75%      6.061307e+07
max      4.250000e+08
Name: budget_adj, dtype: float64

using the above summary we will now create our bin edges.

In [27]:
# creating the bin edges
bin_edges = [9.693980e-01, 3.001611e+07, 6.061307e+07, 4.250000e+08]

and now for the bin names.

In [28]:
# creating the bin names
bin_names = ["Low" ,"Medium" ,"High" ]

now will will use pandas cut to divide the budget_adj column according to bin_edges and bin_names and assign the result to our new column budget_level.

In [29]:
# dividing budget_adj and creating budget_level
budgets['budget_level'] = pd.cut(budgets['budget_adj'], bin_edges, labels=bin_names)

Conclusions

¶

And here now we are going to conclude and summarize the results of our performed investigation and answer the questions posed at the begining:

  1. How did several genres fare through the years? : we selected these genres to investigate ( Action, Comedy, Animation, Horror, Documentary, and Western) of which Comedy genre showed the highest rate of increase and the remaining genres showed also an increase in number of the years except for the western genre.
  1. Does a high budget guarantee a high revenue? and which movie has the highest budget to revenue ratio? : we found that there is a relationship between movie budget and its revenue but it's not that strong, this was indicated by the correlation coefficient which showed a positive but moderate relationship. high budget does not guarantee a high revenue but it helps. The movie with the highest budget to revenue was The Karate Kid, Part II
  1. Does a movie runtime affect the revenue? and is the average movie runtime increasing over the years? : We found that there is a weak positive relationship between the movie runtime and its revenue, indicated by the correlation coefficient. movie runtime does not have a strong effect on the revenues of the movie. also, we found that the average movie runtime tend to decrese over the years.
  1. Who is the most accomplished director in terms of total revenues and total average scores of his movies? : We found that the most accomplished director in terms of total revenues of his movies was Steven Spielberg, and the most accomplished director in terms of the average scores of his movies was Mark Cousins.
  1. Who are the most productive directors in terms of number of movies made? : We found that the top 5 most productive directors are Woody Allen at the top with 45 movies followed by Clint Eastwood then we have a draw between Martin Scorsese and Steven Spielberg then at number 5 we have Ridley Scott with 23 movies.

Limitations

¶

Our above conclusions should be taken with a grain of salt due to some factors we already came across during our analysis but which we are going to state here as a reminder:

  1. This dataset is not equally representative of movies in different years, with the majority of the movies included falling after 2000s. This was clearly seen in the distribution of the release_year column. our first question is the one that is greatly impacted due to this.
  1. The number of the missing values (the high number of zeros) in both the budget and revenue columns was too high, and this made us work with what we could call a sample from these columns because we couldn't afford to have any zeros in our analysis. our second and third questions are the ones most affected because of this.
